<author><name><![CDATA[tepples]]></name></author>
<updated>2018-05-03T07:44:26-07:00</updated>
<published>2018-05-03T07:44:26-07:00</published>
<id>http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=17320&amp;p=217930#p217930</id>
<link href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=17320&amp;p=217930#p217930"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[Re: Megadrive game with 8bit ROM]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=17320&amp;p=217930#p217930"><![CDATA[
Latching the upper and lower bytes on each access and assembling the 16-bit words before they get to the CPU isn't conceptually that different from the N64 RAM being only 9 bits wide and then the RCP memory controller reassembling words before the R4300i sees them. But you'd need a fairly fast ROM for this, and I remember reading somewhere that some early Genesis games couldn't DMA from ROM to VRAM because they were manufactured on slow ROM. Instead, they had to PIO-copy data to VRAM, as if it were a filthy Master System, or copy it to work RAM and then DMA it from there.<br /><br />But I don't see much point, particularly given that the larger 5.0 V EPROMs (27C160 and 27C322) are 16-bit anyway, to the point where people end up using multiplexer circuits to get a 27C322 working with the Super NES's 8-bit data bus. Or were 16-bit EPROMs not made in smaller capacities?<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=9">tepples</a> — Thu May 03, 2018 7:44 am</p><hr />
]]></content>
